description:
This is a used 1,000-gallon propane tank, built to ASME Section VIII, Division 1 code and rated for 250 psig service across a temperature range of -20°F to 125°F, in compliance with NFPA 58. It measures approximately 16 feet long with a 41-inch diameter, and weighs roughly 1,700 to 1,800 lbs empty, depending on whether it's the above-ground or underground configuration — underground tanks ship with a durable ready-to-bury coating (phenolic epoxy powder coat, urethane, or liquid epoxy, depending on manufacturing location), a green composite dome, and an anode stud on the riser pipe for cathodic protection against soil currents.

Filled to the standard 80 percent safety level, this tank holds approximately 800 gallons of usable propane — roughly 73,200,000 BTU at full capacity. That capacity makes it well suited to large commercial kitchens and restaurants, propane resale and bottle-filling operations, agricultural use, and larger homes (generally 4,500 square feet and up) running multiple propane appliances. Two or more 1,000-gallon tanks can be piped together for higher-volume or high-demand service.

As with any propane storage tank, installation must follow state and local codes, including required clearance from buildings and property lines, and — for underground installation — an anode bag placed around the tank for corrosion protection. Being a used tank, condition will vary by unit;

This is a used 500-gallon propane tank, available in above-ground or underground configuration, built to ASME Section VIII, Division 1 code and Class 150 certified. The above-ground version has an elliptical head, measures 9 feet 10 inches long with a 37.5-inch outside diameter, stands 3 feet 11-1/2 inches tall (15-inch leg width, 5-foot leg spacing), and weighs approximately 920 lbs empty. The underground version has a hemispherical head, the same 9-foot-10-inch length and 37.5-inch diameter, a 5-foot 9-3/8-inch riser height, and weighs approximately 953 lbs empty; it ships with a Valspar Q-thane ready-to-bury coating for long-term corrosion resistance underground.

Filled to the standard 80 percent safety level, either configuration holds approximately 400 gallons of usable propane — enough for whole-home heating, hot water, a backup generator, or pool heating, as well as commercial uses such as cooking, dry cleaning, and crop drying, and is generally recommended for homes in the 2,500 to 4,500 square-foot range. Once installed and connected, this Class 150 ASME tank is a fixed, non-portable installation rather than a swappable cylinder.

Being a used tank, cosmetic condition and exact service history will vary by unit;
